    <!-- PlaceHolder tag prevents inline radmenu.ClientID code below clashing with Utility.EnsureScriptManager(this); -->
    <script>

        $(document).ready(function () {
            giveAllMenuLinksAUniqueIdentifier();
            $(".rmLink").on("keydown", setSpacebarToOpenMenus);
        });

        function giveAllMenuLinksAUniqueIdentifier() {
            //Give all menu items a unique attribute value so that I can identify them when spacebar is clicked. Same 'menunumber' attribute is set in .aspx code on menu items.
            var index = 0;
            $(".telerik_main_menu li.rmItem a.rmLink").each(function (index) {
                $(this).attr("menunumber", index);
            });
        }

        function setSpacebarToOpenMenus(e) {
            //Open submenus on spacebar press. 
            var theKey = e.which;
            if (theKey == 32) { // 32 is keycode for spacebar. 
                var menuNumber = $(this).attr("menunumber");
                var menu = $find("ctl00_ContentPlaceHolder1_ctl01_radmenu");
                var menuItem = menu.findItemByAttribute("menunumber", menuNumber);
                var submenuItems = menuItem.get_items();
                if (submenuItems.get_count() > 0) {
                    if (menuItem.get_isOpen() == false) {
                        menuItem.open();
                        e.preventDefault();
                    };
                };
            };
        };

        function ClickItem(menu, args) {
            //Event set in OnClientItemClicking="ClickItem";
            //When user clicks (presses Enter key) a menu item, if submenu is not open, then open it; otherwise navigate to the item's link. 
            var item = args.get_item();
            var submenuItems = item.get_items();
            if (submenuItems.get_count() > 0) {
                //If submenu is closed, then open it; otherwise click the menu item link. 
                if (item.get_isOpen() == false) {
                    args.set_cancel(true); //Cancel the default click action so that it doesn't trigger the menu item's navigation link.
                    item.open();
                }
                else {
                    if (typeof item.redirectToLink == 'undefined') {
                        item.redirectToLink = true;
                        item.click();
                    } else {
                        delete item.redirectToLink;
                    }
                }
            }
        }

    </script>

role="main"><h1>Spotlight on Scholars</h1><div class="ptl_page"><div class="ptl_col_1"><div class="ptl_portlet_vertical"><div class="ptl_top_portlet" style="display:none;"></div><div id="ctl00_ContentPlaceHolder1_ctl07_divContent"><div class="entry">
<p><em>Spotlight on Scholars</em> is a quarterly  feature created to acknowledge the many talented individuals in our  international student and scholar community. Our international  population plays a significant role in research and development, as well  as culturally enhancing our institution.</p>
<h2>Tejabhiram Yadavalli
<br>
<br>
</h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 700;"><img src="/UserFiles/Servers/Server_1497/Image/Spotlight-on-Scholars_Yadavalli_optimized-for-web.jpg" style=""> <br>
</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 700;">Department:</span> Ophthalmology and Visual Sciences <br>
<span style="font-weight: 700;">Home Country:&nbsp;</span>India<br>
<span style="font-weight: 700;">Home Town: </span>Hyderabad</p>
<p class="MsoNormalCxSpFirst">Dr. Tejabhiram Yadavalli is a Postdoctoral Research
Associate in the Ocular Virology Lab, which is within the Department of
Ophthalmology and Visual Sciences in the College of Medicine. Originally from
Hyderabad, India, Dr. Yadavalli heard of UIC from his wife, who is a UIC
graduate. He was drawn to Chicago to be in proximity to world-class
institutions, like UIC, as well as the infrastructure, public transit system,
and Lake Michigan. </p>
<p class="MsoNormalCxSpMiddle">Dr. Yadavalli&rsquo;s research centers on understanding
the cell and molecular biology of herpes simplex viruses. Ocular herpes
infections are the number one cause of infectious blindness in the U.S. He
works in the field of discovery, development, and delivery of antiviral drugs
by testing potential chemicals for their antiviral properties in cells and lab
mice. So far, 3 potential novel therapeutics against Herpes viruses have been
found. Dr. Yadavalli&rsquo;s research involving adding charcoal to the drugs to
increase their efficacy has been published in several journals, such as <a href="http://https://advances.sciencemag.org/content/5/8/eaax0780" target="_blank">Science Advances</a>,
and was also picked up by several websites, including <a href="https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2019/08/190814144500.htm" target="_blank">ScienceDaily</a>, and <a href="https://newatlas.com/activated-charcoal-acyclovir-herpes-treatment/61060/" target="_blank">NewAtlas</a>. This cost-effective, carbon-based drug delivery system can provide
relief for a longer time with fewer doses.</p>
<p class="MsoNormalCxSpMiddle">Dr. Yadavalli hopes to become a Research Assistant
Professor and eventually a tenure-track Professor after his postdoctoral
studies, as he comes from a long line of academics. He enjoys UIC&rsquo;s focus on
research and the sophisticated equipment that is only available through UIC&rsquo;s
Research Resources Center. </p>
<p class="MsoNormalCxSpMiddle">While in the U.S., Dr. Yadavalli has marveled at
our &ldquo;accessibility culture&rdquo; and how the physically challenged can access most
places without relying on external assistance. Going to the <a href="https://www.msichicago.org/" target="_blank">Museum of Science and Industry</a> reminds
him how far humanity has come in scientific advancements; he particularly
enjoys the railroad exhibit. Dr. Yadavalli recommends hitting the tourist spots
in Chicago, like <a href="https://navypier.org/" target="_blank">Navy Pier</a>, boat tours, <a href="https://www.willistower.com/" target="_blank">Willis Tower</a>, or <a href="https://www.lpzoo.org/" target="_blank">Lincoln Park Zoo</a> (visit the tigers in the
summer and penguins in the winter!), but also to try a sensory deprivation
chamber. They are located throughout the city and allow you to meditate or
relax while having all physical senses removed. </p>
<p class="MsoNormalCxSpMiddle">During his search for Chicago&rsquo;s best biriyani, a
famous rice dish from India, Dr. Yadavalli found his favorite so far at <a href="http://www.sirichicago.com/index.php" target="_blank">Siri</a> on Taylor Street. His
favorite Mexican restaurant is <a href="https://www.jarabechicago.com/" target="_blank">Jarabe</a>,
also on Taylor Street; he recommends their chilaquilles. Dr. Yadavalli also
enjoys biking and walking around Chicago. He tries to cover the entire
lakefront trail on his bike and hopes to complete an Olympic triathlon in the
next couple of years! During the cold winter months in Chicago, Dr. Yadavalli
records audio books in Telugu (his native language) to share with his family
and friends. </p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
</div>

<h2 id="SathyaSubramanian">Sathya Subramanian</h2>
<h1><img src="https://www.ois.uic.edu/UserFiles/Servers/Server_1497/Image/SUBRAMANIAN,_Sathya.jpg" style="width: 206px; height: 305px; top: 278px;"></h1>
<p><span style="font-weight: 700;">Department:</span>&nbsp;Disability and Human Development&nbsp;<br>
<span style="font-weight: 700;">Home country:&nbsp;</span>India<br>
<span style="font-weight: 700;">Home Province:&nbsp;</span>Chennai</p>
<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="color: rgb(127, 127, 127);">Sathya Subramanian graduated
with a MS from UIC&rsquo;s Bioengineering program and currently works as an
Assistive Technology Specialist in the Department of Disability and
Human Development. He heard about UIC from his brother who is an alumnus
of UIC. He is originally from the city of Chennai, formerly known as
Madras, TamilNadu in India.</span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="color: rgb(127, 127, 127);">The <a href="https://ahs.uic.edu/assistive-technology-unit">Assistive Technology Unit</a>,
which is part of the Department of Disability and Human development in
the College of Applied Health Sciences, serves people in the community
in their homes, work places or schools to provide services to clients
with disabilities. In his position as an Assistive Technology Specialist
at UIC, Sathya assesses and evaluates on a need-basis, people&rsquo;s access
and independence in using computers and technology. He works with a team
of Rehabilitation Engineers, Occupational Therapists, Physical
Therapists, Speech Language Pathologists and Architects to conduct
research regarding customizable solutions and built-in accessibility
options for technology such as computers, smartphones, and tablets. For
example, 3-D printing is one adaptation that is currently being
developed. Sathya would like to become a certified Assistive Technology
Professional to further hone his skills.</span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="color: rgb(127, 127, 127);">Sathya likes UIC&rsquo;s urban
setting as it gives a great balance between being in a university and a
bustling city. The access to the city for work and leisure is a definite
plus unlike a typical university town. He has learned that indulging in
meaningful conversations with people he does not know is a &ldquo;big yes&rdquo; in
American culture. He has also noticed a keenness in learning about
different cultures from around the world.</span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="color: rgb(127, 127, 127);">He misses his family and friends back home but has a few favorite things in Chicago. His favorite restaurant is <a href="https://www.couscouschicago.com/">Couscous</a> on Taylor street for great food and their awesome chef who inspires him; his favorite location is the observation deck at the <a href="https://360chicago.com/?gclid=Cj0KCQjw-o_bBRCOARIsAM5NbIOezPGv0HGY-MaLvevJ9gTWj-Yb6oJJDCRZ-8BsQXiC6JtlvRtK3KkaAnJaEALw_wcB">John Hancock</a>; and his favorite museum is the <a href="https://www.artic.edu/">Art Institute of Chicago</a>.
He would recommend taking a friend on a long walk along Chicago&rsquo;s
Magnificent Mile and to the observatory at the John Hancock tower.
Outside of Chicago, he likes going on hikes in Northern Michigan for the
breathtaking views.</span></p>
<h2 id="GuipingZhang">&nbsp;</h2>
<h2 id="GuipingZhang">&nbsp;</h2>
<h2 id="GuipingZhang">&nbsp;</h2>
<h2 id="GuipingZhang">Guiping Zhang</h2>
<h1><img alt="GuipingZhang" src="/UserFiles/Servers/Server_1497/Image/USA-1.jpg" style="width: 320px; height: 569px;"></h1>
<p><span style="font-weight: 700;">Department:</span>&nbsp;Chemistry&nbsp;<br>
<span style="font-weight: 700;">Home country:&nbsp;</span>China<br>
<span style="font-weight: 700;">Home Province:&nbsp;</span>Hunan</p>
<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="color: rgb(127, 127, 127);">Guiping Zhang is a Research Scholar from Hunan Province in China. He began his time at UIC in March 2016 with the Department of Medicinal Chemistry and Pharmacognosy in the College of Pharmacy. Dr. Zhang was drawn to UIC due to the reputation of the College of Pharmacy and his previous supervisor, Professor Emeritus, Alan P Kozikowski. Several of Dr. Zhang&rsquo;s professors in China had also previously worked with Professor Kozikowski. Due to Professor Kozikowski leaving UIC to work in a start-up company, Dr. Zhang decided to change departments in January 2018, and is now affiliated with Professor Duncan Wardrop, in the Department of Chemistry.</span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="color: rgb(127, 127, 127);">Dr. Zhang&rsquo;s research involves developing safe and efficient drugs to potentially treat obesity and central nervous system disorders, such as schizophrenia and drug addiction. The drug design focuses on experimenting with subtype-selective and functionally selective 5-HT2c receptor agonists, which produce a biological reaction in the body. The hope is the drugs will be more efficient and produce fewer side effects, specifically lethal cardiac vulvopathy, where the heart valve becomes inflamed and stiff.</span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="color: rgb(127, 127, 127);">His research team has several patents pending, which will then be leased to the pharmaceutical industry. Along with his team members, Dr. Zhang won second place for the Innovate@UIC Innovation Prize at the College of Pharmacy&rsquo;s 2017 Research Days. He has also presented his work at the 55th Annual MIKI (Minnesota, Illinois, Kansas, and Illinois) Medicinal Chemistry Meeting and at the 254th American Chemical Society National Meeting. Once he completes his program at UIC, Dr. Zhang hopes to return to his career as an entrepreneur in the pharmaceutical industry in China.</span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="color: rgb(127, 127, 127);">Dr. Zhang misses his family, including his wife, children and parents, who are all back home in China. He also misses the river around his childhood village where he would often see fish jumping. Dr. Zhang is enjoying the varied cuisine of Chicago and would recommend visitors to Chicago take advantage of the many restaurants. His favorites are restaurants in Chinatown, specifically&nbsp;<a href="https://restaurantguru.com/Mala-Temptation-Chicago">Spicy Spirit</a>, and also Thai, Mexican, and Italian restaurants on Taylor Street near UIC&rsquo;s campus. However, nothing is quite like his mother&rsquo;s cooking! His favorite thing about UIC is working with colleagues from many disciplines, such as biology, drug metabolism and pharmacokinetics (DMPK), pharmacology, and more. Outside of his research, Dr. Zhang likes using the gym to keep up his good health and also to meet new friends from other UIC departments.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-size: 1.8rem;">&nbsp;</span></p>
<p><a name="LiekeVanHeumen"></a></p>
<hr width="100%" size="2">
<div class="postmetadata">
<h2 id="LiekeVanHeumen">Lieke van Heumen</h2>
</div>
<div class="postdate">&nbsp;</div>
<div class="entry">
<h1><img src="/UserFiles/Servers/Server_1497/Image/Photos/Lieke_headshot.jpg" style="width: 206px; height: 305px; top: 278px;"></h1>
<p><strong> Department</strong>: Disability and Human Development<br>
<strong> Home country</strong>: The Netherlands<br>
<strong> Home Town</strong>: Oss</p>
<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="color: rgb(127, 127, 127);">Lieke is a Postdoctoral Research
Associate in the Department of Disability and Human Development. She is
originally from Oss, The Netherlands. Her research at UIC focuses on the aging
of individuals with intellectual and developmental disabilities. It is
interdisciplinary, drawing from the fields of critical social gerontology,
Disability Studies and intellectual and developmental disabilities. She bridges
aging and disability theories and methods to further our understanding of aging
with disability. She promotes a vision of aging that recognizes both
&ldquo;ablebodiedness&rdquo; and disability as valid parts of the aging experience. Lieke&rsquo;s
research methodology is guided by the disability rights&rsquo; philosophy: &ldquo;Nothing
about us, without us.&rdquo; By designing accessible research materials and methods
she enables people with disabilities to fully participate in the research
process, allowing her to retrieve their perspectives on their lives and needs. </span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="color: rgb(127, 127, 127);">Lieke learned about UIC when she
was completing her Master&rsquo;s in Psychology in the Netherlands. She was
interested in the aging of people with intellectual disabilities and knew of
Dr. Tamar Heller&rsquo;s work in the Rehabilitation Research and Training Center on
Developmental Disabilities and Health within UIC&rsquo;s College of Applied Health
Sciences.&nbsp; She was excited to come to
Chicago to learn about the research done at the Center and to participate in
it. This is her first time in the U.S. </span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="color: rgb(127, 127, 127);">Lieke most misses her family,
but also the wonderful Dutch food and biking through the Dutch country side.
When her friends come to town, she likes to take them on the Architectural
River Tour to see Chicago from a different perspective. She has enjoyed
spending time at the lake and the lakefront trail and she also loves the Dutch
Indonesian Restaurant &lsquo;<a href="http://www.dequay-chicago.com/">de Quay</a>&rsquo;. She enjoys playing music and is the flugelhorn
player with the <a href="http://original.chicagobrassband.org/index.php">Chicago Brass Band</a> (an international award-winning 30-piece
brass and percussion ensemble). They promote the British brass band tradition,
but with Chicago flair. She also enjoys traveling the U.S. with her husband who
is a pilot. Lieke enjoys all the community engagement work her department does,
as well as the diversity on the UIC campus. She hopes to secure a faculty position
after the completion of her postdoc position</span></p>
</div>
<p>&nbsp;<a id="Bamisaye_Oyawaluja"></a></p>
<hr width="100%" size="2">
<div class="postmetadata">
<h2>Bamisaye Oyawaluja</h2>
</div>
<div class="postdate">&nbsp;</div>
<div class="entry">
<h1><img src="/UserFiles/Servers/Server_1497/Image/Photos/Bamisaye%20Oyawaluja.JPG" style="width: 320px; height: 240px;"></h1>
<p><strong> Department</strong>: Medicinal Chemistry and Pharmacognosy<br>
<strong> Home country</strong>: Nigeria<br>
<strong> Home Town</strong>:  Lagos</p>
<p>Bamisaye is a Research Scholar in the Department of Medicinal Chemistry and Pharmacognosy in the College of Pharmacy. He is originally from Lagos, Nigeria&rsquo;s most populated city and commercial center. His research involves isolating the medicinally active compounds in a Nigerian medicinal plant in the hopes to chemically synthesize these compounds. This plant is used to treat coughs, toothaches, fevers (including malaria), venereal diseases, high blood pressure, and intestinal parasites. The powdered form of the plant can also be applied to wounds and sores. The aim of the research is to isolate the compounds responsible for the treatments which could lead to new antibiotics, antiulcer, and antihypertensive medications. Other cures or treatments may also be found through additional testing. The research at UIC will be used to complete his PhD at the University of Lagos.</p>
<p>Bamisaye first heard of UIC from his supervisor back home and from a colleague who came to UIC previously. The modern equipment and environment at UIC, including the abundance of quality mentors, faculty members, and researchers, are what Bamisaye enjoys most about researching at UIC. He plans to finish his PhD and hopes to become a professor one day. </p>
<p>Bamisaye misses his family the most &ndash; his wife, 3 brilliant sons, and his mother. He gets a taste of home through cooking and has found Nigerian products and ingredients here in Chicago. He is learning many things about American culture including punctuality, time management, and our often direct approach to things. As he arrived in early fall of 2016, he has not yet explored Chicago as much as he hopes to once the weather is better. Bamisaye plans to visit Navy Pier, Millennium Park, Buckingham Fountain, and the Field Museum of Natural History. Outside of research, Bamisaye enjoys reading, watching football (soccer), listening to news about everything from politics to sports, and meeting new people and making friends.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
</div>
<div class="postmetadata">
<hr width="100%" size="2">
<h2 id="fabiendachet">Fabien Dachet</h2>
</div>
<div class="postdate">&nbsp;</div>
<div class="entry">
<h1><img alt="FabienDachet" class="alignleft size-medium wp-image-6037" src="/UserFiles/Servers/Server_1497/Image/Photos/Fabien Pic 2.jpg" width="320" height="240"></h1>
<p><strong> Department</strong>: Neurology &amp; Rehabilitation<br>
<strong> Home country</strong>: France<br>
<strong> Home Town</strong>: Clermont-Ferrand</p>
<p>Fabien Dachet is a Research Specialist in the Department of Neurology and Rehabilitation at the Illinois Neuropsychiatric Institute.   Prior to coming to UIC, he was a postdoc at Wayne State University at the College of Medicine, in the Department of Neurology.  Before coming to the U.S., Fabien received his Ph.D in Microbiology from Laval University in Quebec City, Canada.</p>
<p>Fabien is from Clermont-Ferrand, France. What he misses most about Clermont-Ferrand is the relaxing way of life, the food, and the arts. Clermont-Ferrand is in central France, west of Lyon. It is also one of France&rsquo;s oldest cities.  It is home to the Puy-de-D&ocirc;me, a volcano that is part of the Chaines des D&ocirc;mes. It is also home to the sculpture Vercingetorix, by Fr&eacute;d&eacute;ric Bartholdi.  Bartholdi was also responsible for creating the Statue of Liberty.</p>
<p>Fabien is passionate about his research.  He states his favorite thing about his work at UIC is, &ldquo;exploring the electric activity of the human brain and actively developing a new type of genetic medications targeting the real causes of epilepsy.&rdquo; He then goes on to add, &ldquo;By comparison, to the surgery used nowadays to cure patients, these new medications have the potential to lead to a cure for epilepsy with a less invasive outcome for patients.&rdquo;</p>
<p>Outside of work, he enjoys different styles of music. Some of the groups he is currently listening to are:  The Plain White T&rsquo;s, Nine Inch Nails, Radiohead, Depeche Mode, Daft Punk, as well as many more.  During the spring he likes to garden. In the summer he appreciates road trips on his motorcycle.  His favorite food is cheese and a glass of wine and his favorite dish to cook is crepes.  He also proclaims that he makes the best crepes in Chicago!  If one is looking for a great place to eat, Fabien&rsquo;s favorite restaurant in town is Cyrano&rsquo;s Farm Kitchen, located on North Wells Street, in the River North neighborhood.  He highly recommends this restaurant because of Chef Didier.  He says, he is an extremely talented cook that brings French culinary art to its best. He also says, the Chef delivers &ldquo;authentic French farm food.&rdquo;</p>
<p>Fabien also finds time for other activities such as reading, and outdoor sports. His favorite sports are volleyball and soccer. His favorite book is <em>Nature&rsquo;s Destiny</em>, by Michael Denton. Fabien says the author was able to put &ldquo;science through a global point of view by doing a scientifically accurate unification of the fields of philosophy, physics and genetics, by doing this, Michael Denton&rsquo;s success to give sense and reason to the whole picture of science, life and religion where no one before him managed.&rdquo;</p>
<p>If you&rsquo;re new to Chicago, he highly recommends visiting all of Chicago&rsquo;s different art museums.  He also encourages biking along the lake front.</p>

<div class="postmetadata">
<h2>Kathryn Wenham</h2>
</div>
<div class="postdate">&nbsp;</div>
<div class="entry">
<h1><img alt="" src="/UserFiles/Servers/Server_1497/Image/Photos/kathrymwenham.jpg" width="221" height="275"></h1>
<p><strong> Department</strong>: Criminology, Law and Justice</p>
<p><strong> Home country</strong>: Australia</p>
<p><strong> Home town</strong>: Brisbane</p>
<p>Kathryn Wenham is a Ph.D student studying Public Health from Griffith University in Australia.  She is currently here at the University of Illinois at Chicago as a student intern conducting research for her dissertation in the Department of Criminology, Law and Justice.</p>
<p>The focus of her research is a comparative analysis on health, wellbeing, education, and cultural constructions of gender interaction in the African immigrant community in Brisbane, Australia and Chicago.   Her research looks at changes in food and diet, socioeconomics, education, gender and gender roles.  Initially when she started it was by making a correlation between traditional diet and long term health versus adapting to a Western diet.   Gender is looked at and how relationships are affected during the process of adapting to a new culture and environment. Kathryn was drawn to this because it is fascinating to her and there has not been a lot of research done on this topic.</p>
<p>Kathryn&rsquo;s home town is Brisbane, Australia.  Brisbane is the capital city of Queensland, and is the third largest city in Australia.   Brisbane is a city that has many immigrants which influences many of the cuisines there.  Kathryn&rsquo;s favorite foods derive from Mediterranean and Thai cooking. However when cooking, her favorite dish to make is a dessert called &ldquo;Pavlova.&rdquo;  Pavlova is a meringue based dessert topped with fresh fruit and cream.  There is a friendly argument between Australians and New Zealanders though as to where the origins of Pavlova have come from, Australia or New Zealand?</p>
<p>What Kathryn misses most about home are her friends and summer activities.  For example, she misses going to the beach, picnics in the park, and African and Brazilian dancing.  Kathryn has been doing both types of dance for 10 years.  Her favorite style though is &ldquo;Samba de Gafieira,&rdquo; a Brazilian form of dance that she performed with her dance school in Rio De Janiero at a dance congress there.  Kathryn recommends any form dance to meet new people and one does not even need to speak the same language.</p>
<p>Kathryn&rsquo;s favorite film is based on the book by Yann Martel, Life of Pi. It is a story about a boy and a tiger that are dependent on each other for survival while stranded on the ocean on a small boat after their ship has sank.  What Kathryn found most appealing about the film besides imagery was how dissociation can be used in surviving trauma.  For books, she prefers biographies about ordinary people who survive extraordinary difficulties and circumstances.  Kathryn, not putting fiction completely aside though, recommends, The Life and Times of the Thunderbolt Kid, by Bill Bryson.     It is a story about growing up in the Midwest during the 1950s.  The story and the characters made her laugh out loud.</p>
<p>For local activities in Chicago, Kathryn recommends visiting her favorite, the Field Museum.  She is a self-proclaimed geek regarding all things related to anthropology.  She loves the cultural display at the Field Museum, specifically the African exhibit.   Other Chicago activities and places Kathryn suggests are taking the Chicago Architectural Boat Tour, visiting The Old Town School of Folk Music, for a show or a class in music or dance.  It recently featured Ladysmith Black Mambazo, and an Australian favorite, singer and songwriter Paul Kelly.  She also recommends doing some shopping, visit the summer festivals, and explore different neighborhoods like Hyde Park</p>
<p><img src="/UserFiles/Servers/Server_1497/Image/Photos/pavlova.png" alt="Pavlova" width="171" height="132"><br>
&nbsp;</p>

<div class="postmetadata">
<h2>Roger Knight Madrid</h2>
<h1><img alt="" class="alignleft size-medium wp-image-6037" title="rogerknightmadrid" src="/UserFiles/Servers/Server_1497/Image/Photos/rogerknightmadrid.jpg" height="300"></h1>
<p><strong> Department</strong>: Community Health Sciences in the School of Public Health</p>
<p><strong> Home country</strong>: Panama</p>
<p><strong> Home town</strong>: Panama City</p>
<p>Originally from Panama City, Panama, Roger Night Madrid has been  working as a Visiting Research Specialist in the Department of Community  Health and Development at UIC since July 2010.  His focus is with the  Community Outreach and Engagement team with the National Children&rsquo;s  Study, a longitudinal study on children&rsquo;s health from birth to age 21.   The National Children&rsquo;s Study has allowed Roger to meet new people  across the Chicagoland area, and promoting and developing partnerships  with a multitude of organizations that benefit the communities.</p>
<p>Traversing Chicago has afforded Roger the opportunity to take in some  of the cultural aspects of Chicago.  Roger recommends the Chicago  Architectural Boat Tour. Recently, his parents were visiting him and  they took part in this tour.  It is a great way to see more of the  Chicago skyline, and to get some of the historical details.  While on  the tour, Roger&rsquo;s mother remembered a scene from the comedy film &ldquo;My  Best Friend&rsquo;s Wedding,&rdquo; starring Julia Roberts.  This is one of many  films done in Chicago that uses the landscape and architecture, creating  more than scenery or a backdrop, but creating another character outside  of the actors in these films.</p>
<p>Roger&rsquo;s current favorite book series is the Hunger Games Trilogy. He  describes it as transporting the reader to a &ldquo;future dystopia,&rdquo; or an  anti-utopia where the inhabitants fight for survival in a  post-apocalyptic world.  A new film based on the novels is scheduled for  release in March 2012 so you can check out what the Hunger Game really  are.</p>
<p>Chicago&rsquo;s restaurants and comedy clubs are high on Roger&rsquo;s list of  Chicago&rsquo;s treasures.  His most recent find is the new restaurant Morso,  in Lincoln Park, from the creator of Gaztro-Wagon Food Truck, Chef Matt  Maroni.   Roger highly recommends Morso for the food, excellent service,  and laid back atmosphere.  For comedy, Roger&rsquo;s favorite recent find is  the troupe &ldquo;Neo-futurists&rdquo; and their show, &ldquo;Too Much Light Makes the  Baby Go Blind,&rdquo; in the Andersonville neighborhood.  Audience  participation is sought after and encouraged during this production.   The Neo-futurists attempt to do 30 plays in one hour with this show!</p>
<p>Sports entertainment is also something Roger finds time for. Prior to  Roger&rsquo;s work at UIC, he studied at the University of Notre Dame in  Indiana.  During his studies there he learned about American football,  became a self- proclaimed &ldquo;avid Notre Dame Fan,&rdquo; and he continues to  follow the Fighting Irish. Sometimes he is able to attend the games in  South Bend through the Alumni Club.  If he is unable to make it, he  knows of a few Chicago locales with televisions that also follow Notre  Dame, where he can watch the game with friends, almost as if he were  there in person.</p>
<p>Living in Chicago has made Roger somewhat nostalgic for Panama at  times.   There are also some things from Panama that cannot be replaced  or replicated.   The food he misses most from home is the Panamanian  version of the tortilla, which he will eat with his favorite, the  Panamanian breakfast of steak, fried eggs, onions, with queso fresco,  served with Panamanian style tortillas. The tortillas he describes as,  &ldquo;&hellip;thick corn cakes that are fried&hellip;&rdquo;  When he travels home he brings  these delicious corn cake tortilla delights back to Chicago frozen so he  can make this traditional Panamanian breakfast anytime.</p>
<p><img alt="Typical Panamanian Breakfast" src="/UserFiles/Servers/Server_1497/Image/Photos/Typical Panamanian Breakfast.jpg" width="200" height="150"><br>
&nbsp;</p>

<h2>Louise Flensted-Jensen R&oslash;nberg</h2>
<div class="postdate">&nbsp;</div>
<div class="entry">
<h1><img alt="Louise Flensted-Jensen Ronberg" src="/UserFiles/Servers/Server_1497/Image/Photos/louise-pic-300x270.jpg" width="270" height="243"></h1>
<p><strong> Department</strong>: Curriculum and Instruction</p>
<p><strong> Home country</strong>: Denmark</p>
<p><strong> Home town</strong>: Skovlunde, suburb of the capital city Copenhagen</p>
<p>Ms. Louise Flensted-Jensen R&oslash;nberg, is currently working as a student  intern and doing research for her dissertation in the Department of  Curriculum and Instruction in the College of Education. &nbsp;Louise&rsquo;s  dissertation titled &rdquo;Components of Children&rsquo;s Reading Comprehension,&rdquo; is  part of her Ph.D. studies a the University of Aarhus.&nbsp; Her research  focuses on learning new techniques with an emphasis on learning to read,  reading comprehension and vocabulary.</p>
<p>By being a parent of three children attending public schools in the  Chicagoland area, Louise will also gain further insight of the education  system of the United States through her own children&rsquo;s perspectives  that will inform her research. This experience allows her to compare the  differences in the teaching styles and methods used in the United  States and Denmark.</p>
<p>When it&rsquo;s time to relax, Louise enjoys a wide range range of music  from Classical, to Jazz, Rock and Blues.&nbsp; Her favorites include Eric  Clapton,&nbsp; Aretha Franklin, Stevie Wonder, and the Beatles, to  Scandinavian artists such as Swedish jazzists Lisa Nilsson and Real  Group.&nbsp; For culinary treats, Louise also enjoys a wide array of  cuisines, two of her favorites are Italian and Thai.&nbsp;&nbsp; When she has  leisure time for reading, she&nbsp; looks to both fiction and non-fiction  genres, including books by author John Irving.&nbsp; Among her favorites is  Immaculee Ilibagiza&rsquo;s,&nbsp; &rdquo;Left to Tell,&rdquo; a autobiographical tale of  survival during the Rwandan genocide.&nbsp; For inspiration for life and  learning, she looks to the Bible, which she refers to as &rdquo;the big book.&rdquo;</p>
<p>Louise&rsquo;s entire family shares her love for learning, travel, and the  arts.&nbsp; In addition to her family with her here in Chicago, she keeps in  close touch with her siblings back home and their wonderful  accomplishments. &nbsp;Her brother is a pianist and her sister is currently  working on her master&rsquo;s thesis in film and media studies.</p>
<p>Since coming to Chicago, Louise has found time to visit the John  Hancock Restaurant and Observatory on the 95th floor, one of the most  recommended sites in the city.&nbsp; The skyscraper&rsquo;s views are impressive  and do not disappoint.&nbsp;&nbsp; Never forgetting her civic responsibilities  back home, Louise voted in a recent election at the Danish Consulate.</p>
<p>As Louise is getting acclimated to life in Chicago she finds she  misses the Danish bakeries from home, particularly the Danish rye bread,  but she found that IKEA sells a comparable Swedish Rye Bread mix that  she is able to use for the time being.&nbsp; Avid animal enthusiasts  (Louise&rsquo;s nickname is <em>Misser</em>, which means &rdquo;cat&rdquo; in Danish), she  and her family miss their Australian Parrot, a Blue Budgeriagar.&nbsp; As a  temporary replacement for the beautiful bird is a Lego lizard that the  family purchased from the Lego store in Schaumburg to keep them company  while Louise completes her dissertation research.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>

She completed her studies,  including a specialization in Ophthalmology, in Mumbai and Chennai,  India.</p>
<p>Although she is very happy in Chicago, she misses her family and  friends back home, as well as the flavorful local food, and riding her  motorbike. <p>Koushik Banerjee is a PhD student in Electrical Engineering with a  focus on solid-state devices. Solid state devices are a contrast to  older devices such as hard drives found in your computer.  Koushik  explains, &ldquo;In my research, I get a chance to deal with all aspects of  solid-state devices, starting from (the) design of the device to its  fabrication, characterization and data analysis. That gives me an  all-around experience and expertise&rdquo;.  Koushik&rsquo;s next project may end up  in your laptop!</p>
<p>Although he is a master with electronics, Koushik admits he cannot  cook but that does not stop him from enjoying a variety of cuisines.  Some of his favorite cuisines are Indian, Chinese, Thai, Japanese,  Middle-Eastern, Ethiopian, and Italian just to name a few.  With  Koushik&rsquo;s never-ending list of favorite foods, he feels that Chicago is  the right place to be to try out all the different cuisines.</p>
<p>In his spare time, Koushik enjoys exploring the Museum Campus  located on the lakefront. The Museum Campus includes the Field Museum  of Natural History, Shedd Aquarium and Adler Planetarium.  Koushik  recommends everyone to visit the Museum Campus because it gives a  splendid view of the Chicago skyline.  Koushik says, &ldquo;You immediately  realize that you are in a great city. At the same time, you can  experience the lake, the vast waterbody stretching up to the horizon. It  is relaxing.&rdquo;</p>
<p>One of his favorite books is a Bengali classic called &ldquo;Chander Pahar&rdquo; (Mountain&nbsp;of Moon) by Bibhutibhusan Bandyopadhyay.  In the adventure novel, Shankar, a young man that recently graduated  from college goes to Africa in pursuit of a hidden treasure.  In  Koushik&rsquo;s words, &ldquo;The adventure in the book is extraordinary and I can  so easily relate to the main character in the story.&rdquo;  For UIC&rsquo;s  international students coming to the U.S. in search of education (and  hidden treasure), they can definitely relate to Shankar&rsquo;s journey except  that they will have to survive pop quizzes and papers rather than  poisonous snakes and man-eating lions.</p>
<p>Koushik&rsquo;s Awards and Recognitions:</p>

    <li>Received the Chancellor&rsquo;s Student Service Award 2009-10 for  accomplishments in a leadership role within student organizations at UIC</li>
    <li>Received the Chicago Consular Corps Scholarship 2007-08 for  Excellency in research and academic standing; Awarded to ten  graduate/undergraduate students at UIC</li>
    <li>Ranked 20th in the state of West Bengal, India in the Higher Secondary Examination, 2001 among approx 0.2million students</li>

<p><strong> Job title</strong>:  Assistant Professor of Urology<br>

<p>Dr. Leslie &ldquo;Les&rdquo; Deane joined UIC&rsquo;s Department of Urology in August  2007. He has also co-authored many peer  reviewed publications, and has done many video presentations.</p>
<p>Even though Les puts in a lot of hours in the Urology department, he  is still able to enjoy the city of Chicago.    The lake front is a  favorite spot for him to relax and enjoy the scenery. <p>For those who are visiting Chicago, he recommends that you visit in  the summer for a number of art and street festivals that take place. <p>Since completing her Ph.D. in Computer Science from the College of  William and Mary, Zhichun has worked in the Department of Electrical  Engineering at UIC as an Assistant Professor, specializing and  publishing many articles in the field of Computer Science.  Her favorite  part of her research is searching for solutions to intellectually  challenging questions.</p>
<p>Personally, although her favorite thing to do in Chicago is visiting  the lakefront and finding a great place to relax, she does miss her  family, friends, and food back home.  For a little taste of home, she  prepares her favorite dish, &ldquo;Pork Rib Soup&rdquo; and listens to Chinese folk  music.  If a friend were to visit Chicago, she would recommend that they  pay a visit to Navy Pier.  When Zhichun is not working on the next  generation of computers, she knits as a hobby and takes care of her pet  fish.</p>
<p>To find out more about the work and research Zhichun is doing and see  a list of her selected publications.  You may also have seen <a href="http://www.uic.edu/htbin/cgiwrap/bin/uicnews/articledetail.cgi?id=14022">Dr. Zhu featured in the March 17, 2010 Edition of UICNews</a>.</p>
<p><img alt="Pork Rib Soup" src="/UserFiles/Servers/Server_1497/Image/Photos/pork-rib-soup.jpg" width="200" height="150"></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
</div>
